    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Pricing Strategy</title>

    <summary>A value-based framework for setting prices: calculate cost floor, estimate customer value ceiling, research willingness to pay, choose a pricing model, and test. Price should be 10–20% of the measurable value delivered — not cost-plus or competitor-copy. Pricing determines business model, customer expectations, and growth trajectory. Cost-plus pricing systematically underprices; competitor-copying ignores value differentiation. Value-based pricing with Van Westendorp research finds the acceptable range empirically, then psychological anchoring maximizes revenue within it.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Pricing determines business model, customer expectations, and growth trajectory. Cost-plus pricing systematically underprices because it ignores the value customers gain. Competitor-copying ignores your differentiation and forces a race to the bottom. Value-based pricing anchors the conversation to ROI, which is the reason customers buy. The Van Westendorp survey method finds the acceptable range empirically without anchoring bias, and psychological pricing tactics (charm pricing, anchoring, decoys) maximize revenue within that range without deceiving customers.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>New product needs initial pricing before launch; no data exists yet</item>
        <item>Existing pricing is below market and owner suspects leaving revenue on the table</item>
        <item>Adding a new tier (freemium, enterprise) and need to define feature gating</item>
        <item>Conversion rate is less than 1% and pricing objections are common — need diagnostic</item>
        <item>Quarterly pricing review cycle; need to compare conversion and churn data against benchmarks</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pricing change affects existing paying customers — requires careful communication strategy beyond agent output; risk of churn spike</item>
        <item>Enterprise pricing involving custom contracts and negotiation — agents can set anchor points but cannot negotiate</item>
        <item>Regulated industries (healthcare, finance, gov) where pricing is constrained by compliance rules</item>
        <item>The product has less than 10 paying customers; there is not enough data for quantitative analysis — do customer interviews first</item>
        <item>Pre-product-market-fit stage — pricing experiments are meaningless without retention signal</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="value-analysis-and-models">
      <p>How to calculate cost floor, measure customer value ceiling, use Van Westendorp surveys to find acceptable price range, and select the right pricing model. An agent is most useful for: (1) structuring the pricing document given cost data, competitor prices, and customer value estimates provided as input; (2) generating the pricing page comparison table and psychological pricing variants; (3) analyzing conversion and churn data by tier and flagging anomalies. The agent should not set final prices — it outputs options with trade-off summaries. A human makes the final call. For price increases on existing customers, require a separate communication review step.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Set price at 10–20% of the measurable value delivered to customers. If your product saves $500/month, charge $50–100/month.</statement>
        <rationale>Cost-plus pricing ignores value and systematically underprices. Competitor-copying ignores differentiation. Value-based pricing anchors the conversation to ROI, which is why customers buy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Cost floor calculation: Sum fixed costs (hosting, tools, salaries), variable costs per customer (support time, API calls), and opportunity cost (your time at hourly rate x hours). This floor is the minimum viable price — below it, the business loses money.</p>

      <p>Customer value ceiling: Quantify value across four types: time saved (hours/month x customer's hourly rate), money saved (cost reduction vs. alternatives), money earned (revenue increase enabled), and risk reduced (cost of problems prevented). The ceiling is the maximum a rational customer would pay.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Ask these four questions to find the acceptable price range: (1) Too expensive? (2) Expensive but worth considering? (3) A bargain? (4) So cheap it raises quality concerns? The optimal price is the intersection of "too cheap" and "expensive" responses.</statement>
        <rationale>Van Westendorp avoids anchoring bias (you don't suggest price points) and surfaces both the floor and ceiling from the buyer's perspective. Minimum sample: 30 target customers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Pricing model selection: Flat rate (simple products with uniform value delivery, one price all features); Tiered/Good-Better-Best (feature differentiation exists, anchors middle tier as obvious choice); Usage-based (value delivery is variable, pay-per-unit aligns cost with value received); Per-seat (team tools where value scales with users, price per user per month); Freemium (high volume low-touch, free tier generates leads, paid converts them); Hybrid base+usage (SaaS with variable infrastructure costs, base covers fixed, usage covers variable).</p>

      <p>Important limitations: Van Westendorp survey data must be collected by humans; agents can design the survey but cannot run it or interpret qualitative nuance. Competitor pricing research is time-sensitive; agent knowledge has a training cutoff and prices change frequently — always verify current prices manually. Willingness-to-pay estimation without real survey data is speculative; agents should mark such estimates as "illustrative" not "research-backed". A/B testing pricing requires proper experimental controls (geo-based or feature-based) that the agent cannot implement — only advise on design. Agents cannot predict churn impact of a price increase; provide historical churn data and let agent model scenarios, not extrapolate from nothing.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="tier-design-and-psychology">
      <p>How to design tier structures (feature allocation, anchor tier), apply psychological pricing tactics, and read signals to raise or lower price. Review pricing at least quarterly; a 12-month window of no pricing change in a growing SaaS means you are almost certainly underpriced.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Design a maximum of 3–4 tiers. Label them by target persona outcome (Starter, Pro, Team), not by technical features (Basic, Advanced, Enterprise).</statement>
        <rationale>More than 4 options causes decision paralysis and lowers conversion. Persona labels help buyers self-select; feature labels force them to compare specs.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Make the middle tier the obvious anchor: give it the name "Pro" or "Growth", badge it "Most Popular", and price it at your target revenue mix. Free/Basic should be limited enough to create genuine upgrade motivation.</statement>
        <rationale>Decoy pricing — the presence of a higher-priced option makes the middle look reasonable. "Most Popular" reduces social risk ("others have chosen this"). Free tier that gives too much removes the upgrade incentive.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Psychological pricing tactics: Charm pricing ($49 vs $50) — left-digit effect makes the number feel significantly lower, use for sub-$200 price points. Round pricing ($100, $500) — signals premium quality, use for high-end enterprise or luxury positioning. Anchor high — show the most expensive tier first (left to right), so middle and lower tiers feel affordable. Annual framing — present as "2 months free" rather than a percentage discount, tangible months feel more concrete than abstract percentages. Always set a price before launching, even if it's wrong — "free for now, will charge later" trains users to expect free access and makes future monetization harder. Charge annually with a 2-month discount (equivalent to ~17% off); annual contracts dramatically reduce churn and improve cash flow predictability. Never show a 12-month plan without showing the monthly equivalent alongside it; hiding the math creates buyer suspicion. Implement a "most popular" badge on the middle tier — it acts as social proof and a decoy that makes the middle tier look optimal.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Raise price when: conversion rate exceeds 5%, customers volunteer "this is cheap", no price objections appear in sales calls, or churn is below 2%/month.</statement>
        <rationale>High conversion at current price means willingness-to-pay is higher. You are leaving revenue on the table. Raise in 20–30% increments and re-measure.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Lower price (or restructure tiers) when: conversion rate is below 1%, price objections appear in more than 30% of sales calls, or sales cycles are unusually long.</statement>
        <rationale>Below 1% conversion signals that price is above willingness-to-pay for this audience. Investigate whether the barrier is price or unclear value before lowering.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Never changing prices after initial launch.</description>
        <reason>Market evolves. Costs change. Competitors adjust. Quarterly price review prevents gradual value misalignment.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Hiding prices behind "contact us" for sub-$1K ARR products.</description>
        <reason>Friction and distrust. Buyers expect transparent pricing for self-serve products. "Contact us" signals the price will be painful or negotiated, which repels price-sensitive early adopters.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <p>Agents applying value-based pricing (10-20% of value) will produce very different numbers depending on how "value delivered" is stated — validate the value assumption before accepting the price output. Van Westendorp analysis requires real survey data; agents cannot simulate population responses — instruct agent to flag all willingness-to-pay outputs as estimates requiring validation. Price recommendations should be labeled as "options" with trade-offs, not "the answer" — the final price decision requires business context the agent does not have. Agents may recommend freemium reflexively for SaaS products; freemium is only appropriate when viral coefficient > 1 or when per-user marginal cost is near zero — prompt agent to justify the recommendation. When analyzing competitor pricing, instruct the agent to note that prices are unverified and may be outdated — hallucinated competitor prices are a common failure mode.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="examples">
      <p>Two concrete examples — SaaS tool and info product — with value analysis, pricing decision, and outcome data.</p>

      <example type="good" title="SaaS Project Management Tool">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Value analysis:
  Saves 5 hours/week per team = $1,000/month value
  Replaces 3 tools = $150/month savings
  Total value delivered: ~$1,150/month

Target price (5-10% of value): $57–115/month

Decision:
  Pro tier: $79/month (full features, primary revenue)
  Basic tier: $29/month (individuals, funnel entry)

Results:
  60% choose Pro
  30% choose Basic
  10% generate enterprise inquiries
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Developer Online Course">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Value analysis:
  Skills learned lead to ~$20K annual salary increase
  Comparable courses: $500–2,000
  Time to ROI: 6 months

Decision:
  Anchor: "$20K salary increase" in headline
  Price: $997 one-time
  Payment plan: 3 x $397

Results:
  70% chose payment plan
  4% conversion from landing page
  (standard for this price range)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

